# Cats vs Dogs Classification using Transfer Learning (MobileNetV2)

## 📌 Overview

Built an image classification model to distinguish between cats and dogs using transfer learning with a pretrained CNN.

✔ Binary classification (Cat vs Dog)
✔ Achieved ~95–98% validation accuracy
✔ Leveraged pretrained features using MobileNetV2

---

## 📂 Dataset

* Dataset: Cats vs Dogs (PetImages)
* Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/crawford/cat-dog-image-classification
* Total Images: ~25,000
* Image Size: Resized to 160×160

### Classes:

```
Cat
Dog
```

---

## ⚙️ Approach

### 1. Data Preprocessing

* Loaded images using `image_dataset_from_directory`
* Resized images to 160×160
* Normalized pixel values
* Handled corrupted images using error filtering
* Applied data augmentation:

  * Horizontal flip
  * Rotation
  * Zoom

---

### 2. Model Architecture

Used pretrained **MobileNetV2** (trained on ImageNet)

```
Input Layer (160×160×3)

Data Augmentation  
Preprocessing (MobileNetV2)

MobileNetV2 (frozen)

Global Average Pooling  
Batch Normalization  

Dense (128) + ReLU  
Dropout (0.5)  

Output Layer (1 neuron, Sigmoid)
```

---

### 3. Training Strategy

#### Phase 1:

* Frozen base model
* Train only top layers

#### Phase 2:

* Unfreeze base model
* Fine-tune with low learning rate

---

## 📊 Results

* Training Accuracy: ~94–96%
* Validation Accuracy: ~96–98%

### 📈 Observations

* Model performs well on clear images
* Misclassifications occur in:

  * Low-quality images
  * Similar-looking breeds
  * Complex backgrounds

---

## 🧠 Key Insights

* Transfer learning significantly improves performance on small datasets
* Pretrained models capture general features (edges, textures) effectively
* Fine-tuning must be done carefully to avoid overfitting
* Data quality impacts model performance more than architecture

---

